# ObsidianKit Quality Guardrails

Apply these for every change unless the user explicitly asks otherwise.

## Delivery Workflow
- Keep changes small and production-ready: implement, run `npm run build`, and fix breakages before finishing.
- Prefer existing patterns and utilities over new dependencies.
- Preserve current UX and avoid regressions in routing, rendering, and tool behavior.

## Performance
- Protect initial load: lazy-load route/tool-heavy code and avoid inflating main bundles.
- Minimize runtime overhead (avoid unnecessary effects, large synchronous work, and repeated parsing).
- For media/file features, prefer browser-native APIs and stream/chunk where possible.
- Keep assets compressed and avoid shipping debug-only code to production.

## SEO
- Ensure each indexable page has accurate title, description, canonical URL, and robots policy.
- Keep structured data valid (JSON-LD) and aligned with visible page content.
- Maintain SEO artifacts in build outputs (`robots.txt`, `sitemap.xml`, prerender/static SEO pages, `llms.txt`).
- Use descriptive internal links between related tools/categories/blog pages.

## Security & Privacy
- Never add secrets, keys, or credentials to tracked files.
- Keep file processing client-side by default; do not introduce silent server uploads.
- Validate and sanitize user-provided content and file metadata before rendering.
- Avoid risky HTML injection; if unavoidable, sanitize strictly.
- Keep third-party scripts minimal, consent-gated, and clearly necessary.

## Pre-Ship Checklist
- Build passes: `npm run build`
- No new lints in touched files
- No secret-bearing files staged
- SEO/static artifacts regenerated if routes/meta changed
